               <label>MSA name (trans.)</label>
               <name xml:lang="ara-x-DMG">Ṣaʕda</name>
               
               <label>Local name (trans.)</label>
               <name xml:lang="ara-Latn" type="latLoc">Ṣaʕdah</name>
            </head>
            <div type="positioning">
               <head>Geo location</head>
               <p>
                  <geo>16°56'N 43°45'E</geo>
                  <country>Yemen</country>
               </p>
            </div>
            <div type="typology">
               <head>Typology (Local)</head>
               <p rend="typology">East (Mashreq) › Arabia › Yemen › Sa’da region</p>
               <p>Sedentary dialect </p>
            </div>
            
            <div type="general">               
               <p>Sa’da is the largest town in the north of Yemen and famous for having been the main seat of the Zaidi Imamate. The dialect of Sa’da and its surroundings is less archaic than other dialects in the region.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div type="researchHistory">               
               <p>The most important study is Part A in <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:U746XQCV">Behnstedt (1987)</rs>, 
               which contains a detailed description of the dialect's phonology and morphology and some remarks on its lexicon. 
               The <hi rendition="#i">Dialect Atlas of North Yemen and Adjacent Areas</hi> <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:BPWSNIY2">Behnstedt (2016)</rs>, 
               no. 237 on the maps) also has abundant data on the dialect.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div type="dictionaries">               
               <p>The comprehensive glossary on Yemeni Arabic in <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:WMBPXL55">Behnstedt (1992-2006)</rs> contains 
               lexical data from Sa’da.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div type="bibliography">               
                    <p xml:space="preserve">To view publications on this variety click <rs type="bibl" ref="bibl:geo:Sa'dah">here</rs>.</p>
                </div>
